	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  valign="top" class="msg" width="100%" >
         
          Ok I feel as if my teacher sucks at explaining his assignment. I don't understand what I’m doing here. I'm really not sure where the value of 'n' comes from,&nbsp;if the user enters it or do I just make it up or what. Can anyone put this in lamens terms for me? <br>    <br>  (1) Completed. <br>   <br>  (2) Write btox() also described in bits.h. Your algorithm should use a static array of 16 hex digits &quot;0123456789ABCDE:. Reading from the right (low) character in the input (binary representation) bitstring, convert each nibble (four bits) into an integer index into the hex digit array. You should see why it is important to go from right to left when the number of bits is not an exact multiple of four. <br>   <br>  (3) Completed <br>   <br>   <br>  /* header file bits.h <br>  <br>  /* function returns in hexstring the hexadecimal representation of <br>  &nbsp;* the bit pattern in bitstring. It is the caller's responsibility <br>  &nbsp;* to have allocated enough space in hexstring (at least  <br>  &nbsp;* 1+ 2*sizeof(int), and to guarantee that bitstring <br>  &nbsp;* contains only the characters '0' and '1'. <br>  &nbsp;* btox must provide the concluding \0 in hexstring. <br>  &nbsp;*/ <br>  void btox(char hexstring[], const char bitstring[]); <br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; /* the const declaration here is necessary to guarantee that the <br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;* called function cannot modify bitstring[], since an array is <br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;* always passed by reference (the array name represents a pointer). <br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;*/ 
          
