	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  width="155" valign="top" class="ultrasmall" nowrap>
        <a href="showProfile.aspx?memid=863" class="subhead" target="_blank">Orocai</a><br>
        
		  <script>titleAndStar(709,0,false,false,"","")</script><br>
		  <div align="center">&nbsp;</div><br>
          Posts:  709<br>
          
          Joined:  11/12/2004 <br>
          
          Status: <span class='offline'>offline</span>
        
		  <img src="image/blank.gif" align="right" border="0" width="155" height="1">
		</td>
        
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  valign="top" class="msg" width="100%" >
         
          Every four binary digits (bits) maps to a single hexadecimal digit. <br>  <br> 0000&nbsp; =&gt;&nbsp; 0 <br> 0001&nbsp; =&gt;&nbsp; 1 <br> 0100&nbsp; =&gt;&nbsp; 4 <br> 1001&nbsp; =&gt;&nbsp; 9 <br> 1010&nbsp; =&gt;&nbsp; A <br> 1110&nbsp; =&gt;&nbsp; E <br>  <br> So, we need to collect groups of four binary digits and translate that into one hex digit in the output.&nbsp; If we process the information left-to-right, then the very first group of binary digits may not be a full set of four.&nbsp; Consider the 11-character string&nbsp; 101&nbsp; 0010&nbsp; 1011.&nbsp; There's a missing high-order 0 on the left; the string is the same as 0101 0010 1011, and should translate to 52B (hex). <br>  <br> One way to do this, as the assignment notes, is to process the string from right to left.&nbsp; That actually strikes me as a bit painful, as you still have to deal with the first (left most) group being less than 4 digits long.&nbsp; Seems to me even easier to dispose of the first group as a special case, and then do the rest of the string. <br>  <br> The mod operator (%) will come in handy here.&nbsp; The input string will be a multiple of 4 digits long, plus some left over.&nbsp; The strlen() function gives you the length of the string.&nbsp; So: <br>  <br> len = strlen(binstring); <br> shortGroupLen = len % 4; <br> numWholeGroups = len / 4; <br>  <br> Now we know how many bits there are in the first group, plus the number of 4-bit groups after that.&nbsp; Let's suppose we had a routine that could take a group of bits and returns the corresponding hex char. <br>  <br> char BitsToHex (char const* bitstring, int numBits); <br>  <br> Then we could write <br>  <br> *hexstring = BitsToHex (bitstring, shortGroupLen); <br>  <br> which gets us the first character.&nbsp; So let's move our pointers along by the sizes of that first group: <br>  <br> hexstring++;&nbsp; // next hex character <br> bitstring += shortGroupLen;&nbsp; // advance shortGroupLen chars in bitstring <br>  <br> And do the same thing for every whole group, in 4 bits to 1 hex digit chunks: <br>  <br> while (numWholeGroups--) <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; { <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; *hexstring++ = BitsToHex (bitstring, 4); <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; bitstring += 4; <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; } <br>  <br>  
          
		  <span class="info">
          					
			</span>
		 
         
         <div align="right">
         <br><span class="ultrasmall">(in reply to <a href='#189322'>Goss</a>)</span>
         
         </div>	
         
		</td>
