	  <tr>
      
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  width="155" valign="top" class="ultrasmall" nowrap>
        <a href="showProfile.aspx?memid=863" class="subhead" target="_blank">Orocai</a><br>
        
		  <script>titleAndStar(709,0,false,false,"","")</script><br>
		  <div align="center">&nbsp;</div><br>
          Posts:  709<br>
          
          Joined:  11/12/2004 <br>
          
          Status: <span class='offline'>offline</span>
        
		  <img src="image/blank.gif" align="right" border="0" width="155" height="1">
		</td>
        
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  valign="top" class="msg" width="100%" >
         
          Pointers are one of those fundamental programming concepts you just need to learn.&nbsp; A pointer is the location of some object, as opposed to the object itself.&nbsp; It's like your home address.&nbsp; You live there, but the address is not you.&nbsp; If I want to visit, I have to go to your address. <br>  <br> You can charge more for &quot;going to&nbsp;an address&quot; if you call it &quot;dereferencing&quot; so that it sounds complicated and technical.&nbsp; So I'll do that.&nbsp; To get from a pointer (address), to the object (say, a character), you dereference the pointer.&nbsp;  <br>  <br> People also use the term &quot;level of indirection&quot; to refer to a pointer.&nbsp; c is a direct reference to a character.&nbsp; p = &amp;c means that p is now an &quot;indirect&quot; reference to c.&nbsp; You can get to c by going through p (that is, by &quot;dereferencing&quot; it).&nbsp; p is one level of indirection removed from c. <br>  <br> The '*' in C is (sometimes) a dereferencing operator.&nbsp; So, <br>  <br> char c;&nbsp; // char c lives somewhere (the linker will figure that out) <br> char* p;&nbsp; // pointer p holds the address of a char <br>  <br> p = &amp;c;&nbsp;&nbsp; // p is set to the address of c <br> c2 = *p;&nbsp;&nbsp; // go to address p and see what char is there.&nbsp; Copy that to c2 <br>  <br> Put a * in front of a pointer, and you have an expression with the value of the object to which the pointer points.&nbsp; Some people like to write their declarations as <br>  <br> char *p; <br>  <br> so that it looks like '*p' is the name of a char, just as <br>  <br> char c <br>  <br> means that 'c' is the name of a char.&nbsp; I happen to prefer to keep the type all together, so I write <br>  <br> char* p; <br>  <br> so that I think that 'p' is the name of a char-pointer.&nbsp; Six of one, half dozen the other.&nbsp; I'll argue the extraordinary virtue of my personal preference and why no right-thinking individual could ever do things the other way some other time. <br>  <br> At any rate, * turns a pointer to the object to which it points.&nbsp; It's the opposite of &amp; (address-of), which coughs up a pointer to the object following it.&nbsp; So: <br>  <br> p = &amp;c; <br> c == *p; <br> c == *(&amp;c); <br> *p == c; <br> &amp;*p == &amp;c; <br> *(&amp;(*p)) == c; <br> p == &amp;c; <br> p = &amp;(*(&amp;c)); <br>  <br> I threw in extra parentheses just to hopefully make it more clear. <br>  <br> You can have multiple levels of indirection, which is to say a pointer-to-a-pointer-to-something.&nbsp; This gets complicated fast, and I'd recommend avoiding it except in certain special cases, until you get used to bopping around levels of indirection in your head.&nbsp; The main case where you just can't avoid a pointer-to-pointer is if you need to pass a pointer to a function and modify it inside: <br>  <br> void FuncModifiesPtr (char** p) <br> &nbsp; { <br> &nbsp; *p = &amp;c;&nbsp; // set parameter to address of c <br> &nbsp; } <br>  <br> char* myP; <br> FuncModifiesPtr (&amp;myP); <br> // at this point, myP == &amp;c <br>  <br> Most programmers would write this as <br>  <br> char* Func (void) <br> &nbsp; { <br> &nbsp; return &amp;c; <br> &nbsp; } <br>  <br> myP = Func(); <br>  <br> which avoids any mention of that extra level of indirection.&nbsp; But sometimes you just can't avoid it because you need to return two values, or because the function return value is used for some other purpose and you also need to return a pointer. <br>  <br> C++ invents the &quot;reference&quot; to avoid this syntactic ugliness. <br>  <br> The other time you're stuck with pointers-to-pointers is with multi-dimensional arrays.&nbsp;  <br>  <br>  
          
		  <span class="info">
          					
			</span>
		 
         
         <div align="right">
         <br><span class="ultrasmall">(in reply to <a href='#189517'>Orocai</a>)</span>
         
         </div>	
         
		</td>
	  </tr>
