	  <tr>
      
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  width="155" valign="top" class="ultrasmall" nowrap>
        <a href="showProfile.aspx?memid=863" class="subhead" target="_blank">Orocai</a><br>
        
		  <script>titleAndStar(709,0,false,false,"","")</script><br>
		  <div align="center">&nbsp;</div><br>
          Posts:  709<br>
          
          Joined:  11/12/2004 <br>
          
          Status: <span class='offline'>offline</span>
        
		  <img src="image/blank.gif" align="right" border="0" width="155" height="1">
		</td>
        
	    <td  bgcolor="dedede"  valign="top" class="msg" width="100%" >
         
          Interesting use of shift to accumulate nibbles.&nbsp; In general, you can convert for any radix by multiplying the accumulated value by the radix, then adding the new value. <br>  <br> <blockquote class="quote"><i>quote:</i><br><br>  <br> int val = 0; <br> for (i = 0; i &lt; strlen(input); ++i) <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; { <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; val = val * radix + valueOfOneDigit(input<i>); <br> &nbsp;&nbsp; } <br> </blockquote> <br>  <br> Shift by 1 is multply by 2, and you've unrolled the loop to execute exactly four times. <br>  <br> The botx() above has a few bugs.&nbsp; It only deals with digits in pairs of groups of four, left-most first.&nbsp; If the bit string is not a multiple of 8 bits long, it will not produce the <font face="times new roman">correct</font> result.&nbsp; Consider the earlier example <br>  <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;101&nbsp; 0010&nbsp; 1011</font> <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;&nbsp; 5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;B</font> <br>  <br> <font face="arial">If the grouping starts at the left, the groups will be</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">1010 0101 011</font> <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;&nbsp; A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3&nbsp; (or maybe&nbsp;6&nbsp;depending on which way the code breaks)</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">The final n++ at the end of btox() is unnecessary.&nbsp; The code does a post-increment every time n2 is used, so n2 always points to the next character to use / first unused character.&nbsp;&nbsp;The extra increment&nbsp;makes the string one character longer than necessary, and you will (in general) get a garbage character at the end of the string.&nbsp; (Most memory is initialized to 0, so most of the time you might get lucky and accidentally get a null terminator as the garbage.)</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">One trick you see people use a lot in this sort of code is to declare a conversion table from integer value to character representation:</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new"><blockquote class="quote"><i>quote:</i><br><br> </font> <br> <font face="courier new"><font face="courier new">char hexDigit[16]&nbsp;= </font> <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; { </font> <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7', </font> <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; '8', </font><font face="courier new">'9', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'&quot; </font> <br> <font face="courier new">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; };</font> <br> </blockquote></font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">With this helper array, you could just write</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">hexdigit[n2++] = hexDigit[ch];</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">without having to use the if (ch &lt;= 9) test.</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br> <font face="courier new">It's somewhat curious that neither ASCII nor EBCDIC put the numerals right next to the alpha characters to make this an easier conversion.&nbsp; Of course, octal was popular back then to avoid the whole question of the glyphs for digits greater than 9, and eight-bit bytes weren't quite nearly as universal.</font> <br> <font face="courier new"></font>&nbsp; <br>  <br>  
          
		  <span class="info">
          					
			</span>
		 
         
         <div align="right">
         <br><span class="ultrasmall">(in reply to <a href='#189719'>Goss</a>)</span>
         
         </div>	
         
		</td>
	  </tr>
